00:36.000 --> 00:38.000
Single sign on

00:38.000 --> 00:40.000
So what's the concept of single sign on?

00:40.000 --> 00:47.000
It's this idea that a user can enter one set of credentials and magically get access to a whole bunch of different systems.

00:47.000 --> 00:49.000
Here's what it basically looks like.

00:49.000 --> 00:51.000
We've got our user system here.

00:51.000 --> 00:55.000
They enter their one set of credentials into the authentication server.

00:55.000 --> 00:59.000
And then they magically get access to a whole bunch of other systems out there.

00:59.000 --> 01:01.000
That's the theory.

01:01.000 --> 01:03.000
That's the idea of single sign on.

01:03.000 --> 01:05.000
So what are the pros and cons of this?

01:05.000 --> 01:07.000
Well, I mean, users love it.

01:07.000 --> 01:09.000
They don't have to remember all these different passwords.

01:09.000 --> 01:15.000
And so potentially they might remember instead of having to remember 10 crappy passwords,

01:15.000 --> 01:21.000
they'll maybe remember one better password, although in my experience that doesn't usually happen.

01:21.000 --> 01:24.000
It also allows for centralized administration.

01:24.000 --> 01:29.000
If you want to create, modify, someone's account, remove someone's account on a whole bunch of systems.

01:29.000 --> 01:32.000
If you're using a single sign on system, it's much easier to do so.

01:32.000 --> 01:34.000
What are the downsides, the cons?

01:34.000 --> 01:40.000
Well, it's absolutely a single point of failure from both an availability and a compromise perspective.

01:40.000 --> 01:45.000
Now let's look at the basics of how any of these single sign on systems work.

01:45.000 --> 01:50.000
The basic idea here is that our user wants to get access to the application.

01:50.000 --> 01:56.000
In order to get access to the application, they'll have to authenticate which the authentication server.

01:56.000 --> 02:00.000
So our user here is going to send a login request to the application.

02:00.000 --> 02:05.000
If our user is currently authenticated if they have a valid ticket or token,

02:05.000 --> 02:07.000
then they'll probably be let right in.

02:07.000 --> 02:10.000
But let's assume that our user doesn't currently have a valid ticket or token.

02:10.000 --> 02:11.000
What's going to happen?

02:11.000 --> 02:14.000
Well, they'll be redirected back.

02:14.000 --> 02:17.000
And then they'll be redirected back to the authentication server.

02:18.000 --> 02:20.000
And what will they do with the authentication server?

02:20.000 --> 02:25.000
Authenticate through knowledge, ownership, characteristic or some combination thereof.

02:25.000 --> 02:31.000
Once they've authenticated with the authentication server, they'll be provided with a ticket or token

02:31.000 --> 02:34.000
and redirected back to the application.

02:34.000 --> 02:39.000
The application will then read the assertion statements, the contents of that ticket or token,

02:39.000 --> 02:46.000
and make an authorization decision as to whether or not that user is able to actually access the application.

02:46.000 --> 02:51.000
So that at a basic level is how any of these single sign-on type systems work.

02:51.000 --> 02:56.000
So now let's look at one particular technology that enables single sign-on, Kerberos.

02:56.000 --> 03:02.000
Kerberos is a pretty old technology, pretty old protocol, and frankly not very good,

03:02.000 --> 03:07.000
but it is commonly pervasively used with an organization to enable single sign-on.

03:07.000 --> 03:11.000
And the reason it's used so pervasively, even though it's not great, it's built into Microsoft products.

03:11.000 --> 03:14.000
It's been used for years, it's just become a standard.

03:14.000 --> 03:16.000
And so why is it called Kerberos?

03:16.000 --> 03:18.000
There's a fun little bit of history behind this.

03:18.000 --> 03:24.000
So in Greek mythology, there's the three-headed dog, Cerberos, guarding the gates to Hades.

03:24.000 --> 03:32.000
And so the creators of Kerberos were creating a protocol that would have sort of three major capabilities,

03:32.000 --> 03:35.000
accounting, authentication, and auditing.

03:35.000 --> 03:40.000
And so they thought of it as a three-headed dog, and so they decided to call it Kerberos.

03:41.000 --> 03:43.000
So let's look at how Kerberos works.

03:43.000 --> 03:47.000
And if you've ever read about Kerberos in a book to figure out all the various pieces of it,

03:47.000 --> 03:52.000
and how ticket-granting tickets, and ticket-granting servers, and KDCs, and anything else fits together,

03:52.000 --> 03:53.000
it's a bit of a nightmare.

03:53.000 --> 04:01.000
So let me try and make it as simple as possible, and highlight just the most key aspects that you need to know about Kerberos.

04:01.000 --> 04:08.000
So first of all, with Kerberos, we have our client here, and we have the service that our client eventually wants to access here.

04:08.000 --> 04:15.000
And in order to access that service, the first thing that our user or client here is going to do, in this case, Alice,

04:15.000 --> 04:20.000
she's going to go to what's called the authentication service, the AS.

04:20.000 --> 04:27.000
And what the AS is going to return back to her is an encrypted ticket-granting ticket, a TGT.

04:27.000 --> 04:33.000
Now, this TGT, this ticket-granting ticket, is encrypted with her password, with Alice's password.

04:33.000 --> 04:38.000
So what Alice decrypts the ticket-granting ticket with is her password.

04:38.000 --> 04:46.000
So now she has a copy of the ticket-granting ticket, and she now makes a request to the ticket-granting service, the TGS.

04:46.000 --> 04:55.000
And what she says to the TGS is, here's my ticket-granting ticket, here's my user information, and here's the service that I want access to.

04:55.000 --> 05:04.000
And then the TGT-granting service will make a decision, and if it decides that she's going to have access, it will return Alice a service ticket.

05:04.000 --> 05:13.000
And it's finally this service ticket that Alice can use to go and access the service that she wants to access.

05:13.000 --> 05:23.000
A few important things here. This ticket or token contains some assertion statements, some information, like Alice's username, and some other assertion statements like that.

05:23.000 --> 05:30.000
But very importantly, does it contain Alice's password or her other authentication credentials? No.

05:30.000 --> 05:36.000
Because you do not want all your different services, your different systems out there, to know Alice's password.

05:36.000 --> 05:41.000
The only system we want to know Alice's password is the authentication service.

05:41.000 --> 05:55.000
Now there's one more bit of terminology you should know here, and that is that these two pieces, the authentication service and the ticket-granting service, are typically sort of bundled together and called the Key Distribution Center, the KDC.

05:55.000 --> 05:59.000
So those are the major pieces of Kerberos that you need to know.

05:59.000 --> 06:08.000
Now let's talk about two major issues with Kerberos. The first is that it only supports symmetric cryptography.

06:08.000 --> 06:18.000
Now of course, we've talked about the major problem with symmetric cryptography is both Key Distribution and the number of keys that you need grows exponentially.

06:18.000 --> 06:29.000
The more systems there are, the environment. So it can be quite difficult to manage the keys in a Kerberos environment because of the fact that only supports symmetric cryptography.

06:29.000 --> 06:36.000
The other issue is that it only supports one ticket-granting ticket. Here's why that's an issue.

06:36.000 --> 06:51.000
It's a very good practice in security to expire someone's access or force them to reauthenticate at a particular interval depending on the value of the system, the more valuable the system, the more often you want that person to reauthenticate.

06:51.000 --> 06:59.000
The same idea applies to Kerberos. So if we want to force a user to reauthenticate, we would expire their ticket.

06:59.000 --> 07:05.000
And let's say they have access to 10 different systems, and one of those systems is a really high-value system.

07:05.000 --> 07:13.000
So you're going to expire that ticket based on the frequency necessary for the really high-value system, maybe every 10 minutes.

07:13.000 --> 07:18.000
But here's the problem. Let's say that our user, even though they have access to the high-value system, they're not using that system.

07:18.000 --> 07:26.000
They're over here using the company Wiki or something, which is a super low-value system, and it would probably be fine if they reauthenticated every decade.

07:26.000 --> 07:36.000
But the problem is because that ticket-granting ticket is set to expire based on the most valuable system, that ticket-granting ticket is going to be expiring every 10 minutes.

07:36.000 --> 07:45.000
And our user here that's accessing this low-value system is being forced to reauthenticate every 10 minutes, very irritating the user, not great.

07:45.000 --> 07:49.000
So those are the two major issues that you should know about Kerberos.

07:49.000 --> 07:59.000
And there's one other major technology that enables single sign on that you need to know about, and it's called sesame, as in open sesame.

07:59.000 --> 08:04.000
Now open sesame addresses the two major issues that we have with Kerberos.

08:04.000 --> 08:09.000
It's those Europeans again, they looked at Kerberos, and they said, we can do better.

08:09.000 --> 08:14.000
And they created sesame. And it addresses the two major issues with Kerberos.

08:14.000 --> 08:24.000
It supports not only symmetric, but also asymmetric keys, and it doesn't issue just one ticket-aid issues, multiple tickets.

08:24.000 --> 08:32.000
So you're very likely to get quite a few questions on Kerberos, so know the most about that one, and you might get one question on sesame if any.

08:32.000 --> 08:37.000
So those are the two major protocols that enable single sign on.

08:44.000 --> 08:49.000
Thank you.

